Mark Edmundson Anemia
Research Interests
My laboratory studies the interdisciplinary field of cellular bioenergetics. I am particularly interested in the fundamental mechanisms responsible for producing and transforming energy in living cells. Our work involves the development and application of innovative biophysical tools to uncover the mechanisms underlying mitochondrial respiration and the regulation of cellular energetics during normal physiology and disease states.
Mitochondrial respiration
Mitochondrial respiration generates the majority of cellular energy via the process of oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) and is central to multiple aspects of norman physiology and disease. Since clinically-relevant disease mechanisms often occur in context of changes in energy production, my laboratory seeks to identify the mechanisms underlying mitochondrial metabolism and how they contribute to cell physiology and disease. In addition, since mitochondrial dysfunction is increasingly recognized as a fundamental mechanism of aging and other age-related diseases, my laboratory seeks to uncover both the cellular mechanisms and objective clinical manifestations of age-related mitochondrial dysfunction. Current research focuses on determining the fundamental mechanisms of mismatched ATP/NADH during hypo- and hyperoxia which represent normal mitochondrial stress, and how they contribute to muscle fatigue and related fatigue syndromes. Related projects involve determining the fundamental mechanisms through which normal and pathological changes in OXPHOS induce chronic resting muscle activity, overt pain and premature aging. My laboratory uses a broad range of cutting-edge experimental approaches to address these challenges.
Regulation of hematopoiesis by mitochondrial respiration
My laboratory has uncovered fundamental new mechanisms linking mitochondrial respiration to hematopoietic stem cell (HSC) biology. These data indicate that OXPHOS is critical to normal HSC activity and that therapeutic interventions that target mitochondrial respiration can markedly influence hematopoiesis. My laboratory is currently attempting to further elucidate the cellular mechanisms underlying this process and their specific contributions to the clinical significance of HSC biology and their pathophysiological alterations in myeloid and plasma cell leukemia. Therapeutic strategies are being developed with a focus on specifically targeting the unique energy metabolism characteristics of HSC mitochondria.
